{{Clickable NHL state map}}
The [[United States]] [[National Historic Landmark]] Program is designed to recognize and honor the nation's cultural and historical heritage.  The program was formally inaugurated with a series of listings on October 9, 1960; as of February 16, 2017, there are 2,596 designated landmarks.  A National Historic Landmark (NHL) is generally a [[National Register of Historic Places property types|building, district, object, site, or structure]], that is officially recognized by the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]] for its national historical significance.  A National Historic Landmark District (NHLD) is a [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] that is recognized as an NHL.  Its geographic area may include [[contributing properties]] that are buildings, structures, sites or objects, and it may include non-contributing properties.

The program is administered by the [[National Park Service]] (NPS), a branch of the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. The National Park Service determines which properties meet NHL criteria and makes nomination recommendations after an owner notification process.<ref name="NHLQA">{{cite web|publisher=National Park Service|title=National Historic Landmarks Program: Questions and Answers|work=National Historic Landmarks Program|url=http://www.nps.gov/nhl/QA.htm|accessdate=September 21, 2007}}</ref> The [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] reviews nominations and, based on a set of predetermined criteria, makes a decision on NHL designation or a determination of eligibility for designation.<ref name="Title36">{{cite web|url=http://www.access.gpo.gov/nara/cfr/waisidx_98/36cfr65_98.html|title= Title 36 of the Code of Federal Regulations, Part 65|publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office|US Government Printing Office]]|accessdate=April 5, 2008}}</ref> Both public and privately owned properties can be designated as NHLs. This designation provides indirect, partial protection of the historic integrity of the properties via tax incentives, grants, monitoring of threats, and other means.<ref name="NHLQA"/> Owners may object to the nomination of the property as a NHL. When this is the case the Secretary of the Interior can only designate a site as eligible for designation.<ref name="Title36"/>

All NHLs are also included on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP), a list of some 80,000 historic properties that the National Park Service deems to be worthy of recognition. The primary difference between a NHL and a NRHP listing is that the NHLs are determined to have national significance, while other NRHP properties are deemed significant at the local or state level.<ref name="NHLQA"/>

==Tabular listing==
Most landmark designations are in one of the [[List of U.S. states|50 states]].  [[List of National Historic Landmarks in New York|New York]] is the state with the most (270), and [[List of National Historic Landmarks in New York City|New York City]], with 114 designations, is the city with the largest number of designations.  Of the states, [[List of National Historic Landmarks in North Dakota|North Dakota]] has the fewest designations with seven.  Three cities (New York City, [[List of National Historic Landmarks in Philadelphia|Philadelphia]], and [[List of National Historic Landmarks in Boston|Boston]]) have enough listings to warrant lists separate from their respective states.

A small number of designations have been made outside the 50 states.  Most of these appear in [[Insular area|United States possessions]].  The [[United States Virgin Islands|Virgin Islands]] have five listings, [[Puerto Rico]] has four, and island possessions in the [[Oceania|South Pacific]] have six.  Five listings are found in Pacific island nations with which the U.S. has established a [[Insular area#Freely associated states|free association agreement]], and one listing, the [[American Legation]] in [[Tangier]] (the nation's first foreign public property), is found in the unaffiliated [[Kingdom of Morocco]].

